---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';

const faq = [
  {
    question: "What is the App Store size limit for iOS apps?",
    answer: "Apps downloaded over cellular are limited to 200MB (raised from 100MB in iOS 13). There is no hard limit for downloads over Wi-Fi, but Apple recommends keeping apps under 4GB total. The install size (on-device) can be larger than the download size because the IPA contains compressed assets that expand during installation."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the difference between download size and install size?",
    answer: "Download size (IPA size) is the compressed bundle transferred from the App Store. Install size is what the app occupies on device after decompression and installation. Install size is typically 2–3x larger than the download size. App Store Connect shows both metrics for each build you submit."
  },
  {
    question: "What is App Thinning?",
    answer: "App Thinning is Apple's process of delivering only the code and resources a specific device needs. It has three components: slicing (device-specific binary variants), bitcode (recompilation by Apple for each chip architecture), and on-demand resources (assets downloaded at runtime). Together, they can reduce delivered app size by 30–60% for asset-heavy apps."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I check my app's size before submitting to the App Store?",
    answer: "Archive your app in Xcode (Product > Archive), then in the Organizer window click 'Distribute App' and choose 'Development' distribution. In the export options, check 'Include app size report'. Xcode generates a detailed breakdown by framework, asset catalog, and binary segment. Alternatively, examine the .ipa file directly — it's a ZIP archive you can unzip and inspect."
  },
  {
    question: "What is On-Demand Resources (ODR) in iOS?",
    answer: "On-Demand Resources let you tag assets (levels, additional content, large media) that are not included in the initial download but are fetched from Apple's servers when needed at runtime. This dramatically reduces initial download size for content-heavy apps like games. The OS caches downloaded resources and purges them if storage is needed."
  },
  {
    question: "Should I use bitcode for my iOS app?",
    answer: "Apple deprecated bitcode for iOS in Xcode 14 (2022). Apps built with Xcode 14+ no longer include bitcode by default, and the App Store no longer processes it. If you're on a newer Xcode version, bitcode is not relevant to your size optimization strategy. The benefits bitcode provided (Apple recompiling for new chips) are now handled differently."
  }
];
---
<BaseLayout
  title="iOS App Size Calculator: Estimate IPA & Download Size"
  description="Understand iOS app size factors, estimate IPA download size, and apply App Thinning, on-demand resources, and asset optimization techniques to meet App Store size guidelines."
  tool="ios-app-size-calculator"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"WebPage","name":"iOS App Size Calculator: Estimate IPA & Download Size","url":"https://devplaybook.cc/tools/ios-app-size-calculator","description":"Understand iOS app size factors, estimate IPA download size, and apply App Thinning to meet App Store size guidelines."})} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">iOS App Size Calculator: Estimate IPA & Download Size</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">Estimate your iOS app's download and install size, understand what drives app size, and apply App Thinning and asset optimization to stay under App Store cellular limits.</p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Size factor breakdown</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> App Thinning guide</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> On-Demand Resources</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Size reduction techniques</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">App Store Size Limits</h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Limit Type</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Size</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 font-semibold">Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="divide-y divide-border">
        <tr>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">Cellular download limit</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">200 MB</td>
          <td class="py-2">User can override in iOS Settings</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">Total app bundle</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">4 GB</td>
          <td class="py-2">Including all on-demand resources</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">On-demand resources per tag</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">512 MB</td>
          <td class="py-2">Hosted by Apple CDN</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">Recommended download size</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">&lt;50 MB</td>
          <td class="py-2">Best conversion rates on App Store listings</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">What Drives iOS App Size</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">Understanding the composition of your IPA helps target the right optimizations. Unzip your .ipa to inspect its contents:</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code class="text-sm"># Unzip and inspect your IPA
cp MyApp.ipa MyApp.zip && unzip MyApp.zip -d MyApp_Contents

# Typical IPA structure:
# Payload/MyApp.app/
#   MyApp              — compiled binary (often the largest single file)
#   Assets.car         — compiled asset catalog (images, colors)
#   Frameworks/        — embedded frameworks (React Native, Hermes, etc.)
#   _CodeSignature/    — code signing data
#   Base.lproj/        — localization strings

# Check sizes of each component
du -sh MyApp_Contents/Payload/MyApp.app/*
du -sh MyApp_Contents/Payload/MyApp.app/Frameworks/*</code></pre>

  <p class="mb-4">In a typical React Native app, size is distributed roughly as follows:</p>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Component</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 font-semibold">Typical Size</th>
          <th class="text-left py-2 font-semibold">Reduction Strategy</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="divide-y divide-border">
        <tr>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">React Native framework</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">8–15 MB</td>
          <td class="py-2">Enable New Architecture (smaller)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">Hermes engine</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">3–6 MB</td>
          <td class="py-2">Already smallest JS engine option</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">JavaScript bundle</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">1–10 MB</td>
          <td class="py-2">Tree shaking, dynamic imports, remove unused deps</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">Images and assets</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">5–50 MB+</td>
          <td class="py-2">WebP format, asset catalogs, ODR</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">Native dependencies</td>
          <td class="py-2 pr-4">2–20 MB</td>
          <td class="py-2">Audit and remove unused native modules</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">App Thinning Techniques</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">App Thinning is automatic when you distribute through the App Store, but you can maximize its effectiveness:</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code class="text-sm"># 1. Use Asset Catalogs for all images
# Xcode compiles .xcassets into Assets.car and generates
# device-specific slices automatically

# 2. Provide 1x, 2x, 3x variants — App Thinning delivers only what's needed
# (iPhone 15 Pro = 3x only, older devices = 2x)

# 3. Convert images to WebP for significant compression
# Use cwebp tool:
brew install webp
cwebp -q 80 input.png -o output.webp
# WebP is 25-35% smaller than PNG at same quality

# 4. Enable vector assets to avoid multiple raster sizes
# In Asset Catalog: Scales = Single Scale, Render As = Template Image</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">On-Demand Resources (ODR)</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">On-Demand Resources let you host large assets on Apple's servers and download them only when needed. Ideal for tutorial content, seasonal themes, or level packs:</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code class="text-sm">// Request an on-demand resource tag in Swift
import Foundation

let resourceRequest = NSBundleResourceRequest(tags: ["level-2-assets"])
resourceRequest.beginAccessingResources &#123; error in
    if let error = error &#123;
        print("Failed to load resources: \(error)")
        return
    &#125;
    // Assets are now available in the app bundle
    let imageURL = Bundle.main.url(forResource: "level2-background",
                                   withExtension: "jpg")
&#125;

// Release resources when done to free device storage
resourceRequest.endAccessingResources()</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Generate an App Size Report</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">Xcode can generate a detailed size report before you submit to the App Store:</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code class="text-sm"># Archive and export with size report
# In Xcode: Product > Archive
# In Organizer: Select archive > Distribute App
# Choose: Development > Next > Check "Include app size report"
# The exported folder contains AppThinning.plist and a size report

# Or use xcodebuild for CI:
xcodebuild archive \
  -workspace MyApp.xcworkspace \
  -scheme MyApp \
  -archivePath build/MyApp.xcarchive

xcodebuild -exportArchive \
  -archivePath build/MyApp.xcarchive \
  -exportOptionsPlist ExportOptions.plist \
  -exportPath build/export/</code></pre>

  <AdUnit slot="auto" format="auto" label="Advertisement" />
  <FaqSection faq={faq} />
  <ToolPageCta currentTool="ios-app-size-calculator" relatedTags={['ios', 'mobile', 'react-native', 'app-store', 'performance']} />
</BaseLayout>
